IN THE 1940'S LIBRARY CUSTODIANS AND THEIR FAMILIES ACTUALLY LIVED IN THE LIBRARY.
MR. CLARK'S FAMILY LIVED IN WASHINGTON HEIGHTS.
WHEN HE WAS A KID, HE THOUGHT THEY WERE RICH.
HIS FAMILY TOLD HIM NO, THEY WERE POOR.
HIS DAD BECAME THE KEEPER OF THE TEMPLE OF KNOWLEDGE.
HE WAS ASHAMED OF WHERE HE LIVED BECAUSE IT WASN'T NORMAL.
HE HAD TO BE VERY QUIET AT HOME DURING THE DAY, BUT AFTER DARK HE COULD RUN AND PLAY IN THE LIBRARY.
IN THE MIDDLE OF THE NIGHT, IF HE HAD A QUESTION, HE COULD GO DOWNSTAIRS AND GET A BOOK TO FIND THE ANSWER UP TO 3 IN THE MORNING.
THE LIBRARY GAVE HIM A THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE.
HE WAS THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE FROM HIGH SCHOOL AND COLLEGE.
HE WAS PROUD TO SHOW HIS DAD THE SIGN ON HIS CLASSROOM DOOR WHEN HE BECAME A TEACHER - PROFESSOR CLARK.
HIS DAD HAD WANTED HIM TO HAVE HIGHER HORIZONS.
HE COULDN'T IMAGINE WHAT HIS LIFE WOULD HAVE BEEN LIKE IF HE HADN'T LITERALLY GROWN UP IN THE LIBRARY.
THERE WAS A PHOTO AT THE END OF RONALD AND JAMILAH CLARK.

THERE WAS A BOY WHOSE NAME WAS RONALD CLARK.
HE THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH BUT THEY TOLD HIM THEY WERE POOR.
ONE DAY, HIS DAD BECAME THE CUSTODIAN OF THE PUBLIC LIBRARY IN WASHINGTON HEIGHTS.
BACK THEN, IN THE 1940'S, CUSTODIANS AND THEIR FAMILIES LIVED IN THE LIBRARY THEY TOOK CARE OF.
HE WAS NOT PROUD OF LIVING THERE, HE WAS ASHAMES.
HE NEVER INVITED HIS FRIENDS OVER TO PLAY.
HE HAD TO BE VERY QUIET DURING THE DAY, BUT AT NIGHT HE COULD RUN AND PLAY IN THE LIBRARY.
IF HE HAD A QUESTION, HE COULD GO DOWNSTAIRS AND GRAB A BOOK AND READ UNTIL 3 A.M.
HE LOVED READING, AND HE BECAME THE FIRST MEMBER OF HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE FROM HIGH SCHOOL AND COLLEGE.
WHEN HE BECAME A TEACHER, HE TOOK HIS DAD TO SEE THE "PROFESSOR CLARK" SIGN ON HIS CLASSROOM DOOR.
HIS DAD WAS QUIET, BUT HE'D WANTED HIM TO RISE TO HIGHER HEIGHTS.
OH, HE CALLED HIS DAD THE KEEPER OF THE TEMPLE OF KNOWLEDGE.
AND THE LIBRARY WAS THE TEMPLE OF KNOWLEDGE.
IT GAVE HIM A THIRST FOR LEARNING.
AT THE END THERE WAS A PHOTO OF RONALD AND JAMILAH CLARK.
